Update: it can be built now, and I got the xcframework `build/iOS_framework/framework_out/onnxruntime.xcframework`.

But it only compiles a `C++` API, and I struggled to find where to specify it to compile with an `Object-C` API. Any hints on this? Thanks a lot!

The Objective-C API is packaged as a CocoaPods pod (onnxruntime-mobile-objc). In that configuration, it's not compiled into ORT but rather depends on the ORT library and C/C++ API (another pod, onnxruntime-mobile-c).

The simplest way to test out the Objective-C API with your custom build would be to start with a release version (e.g. 1.9) and download the release pods, then drop in your updated onnxruntime.xcframework.

You could also build the pods.
This script may be useful:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/c30cc9190a956b9d3a24639681699b8404ad36e7/tools/ci_build/github/apple/objectivec/assemble_objc_pod_package.py
And the CI build that creates the packages:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/c30cc9190a956b9d3a24639681699b8404ad36e7/tools/ci_build/github/azure-pipelines/mac-ios-packaging-pipeline.yml#L58-L105
It currently uploads the package zip archive and points to that from the podspecs, but you could change that to a local path or something else.

Hi @edgchen1, thank you for the suggestions. It does help me understand how it works. I tried the below steps and got the errors in the screenshot. 1) downloaded and installed the 1.9.0 release `onnxruntime-mobile-objc` pod 2) replaced the Header files in `{project_root}/Pods/onnxruntime-mobile-c/Headers` with the ones that I built (from my `xcframework`) 3) replaced the `{project_root}/Pods/onnxruntime-mobile-c/onnxruntime.xcframework` with the `xcframework` that I built. The Xcode prompts errors for `Empty paragraph passed to '\param' command`. It seems like the object-c and C++ APIs are not well aligned. I packed the updated `{project_root}/Pods` directory of mine into the attached file for reference. Any guidance for what I did wrong? I'm new to object-c, your help and patience would be really appreciated! Thanks a lot [Pods.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/7240299/Pods.zip)

I guess you are building from some more recent code. There were documentation updates (since the release branch was made) that Xcode complains about, so we disabled them like this: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/d3f859fe3063bdfc4b2fdadbd46985b3742b9aec/objectivec/src/cxx_api.h#L6-L14 This was one fix to the Objective-C code but I think it should be ok to use the 1.9 version if you worked around this issue. Its usage of the C/C++ API hasn't changed recently. But to be safe in case other issues arise, you could try building your custom build from 1.9 too. BTW, we plan to come up with an easier way to package a custom built ORT into pods.

I will try 1.9.0 to see whether the problem exists.

Based on your `reduced_build_config`, there are some operators which is not yet supported by CoreML execution provider, this will create graph partitioning between ORT CPU execution provider and CoreML execution provider, which will slow down the performance, and will offset the perf gain by using hardware acceleration, for this model, probably using ORT CPU execution provider (without CoreML) will have better performance.

CoreML execution provider does not accept models with dynamic input shape, if your model has dynamic input shape, all the execution will fall back to CPU execution provider. The may explain the similar latencies for executions with different execution providers.

Try to see if this one appears in the logs,
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/4a1b386f7cd207e580add1ef0788a3c973f633f1/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/builders/helper.cc#L61

With the verbose log level you should be able to see these logs:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/4daa14bc74b5378d5fcb0d6de063a9fa8bd42eac/onnxruntime/core/providers/coreml/coreml_execution_provider.cc#L82-L94

That shows how many nodes are supported by the CoreML EP.

Thank you @gwang-msft @edgchen1!
That makes sense. My model does have dynamic input and output shape. However, I failed to find that log info. 

I set `env` and `options` both to verbose mode already. But cannot find coreml ep related messages in the log. Below are what I got. Note that I used CoreML CPU only when creating the session but it says `Adding default CPU execution provider` in the log without notifying any warnings for dynamic input/coreml capability.

```swift
  env = try ORTEnv(loggingLevel: ORTLoggingLevel.verbose)
  let options = try ORTSessionOptions()
  try options.setLogSeverityLevel(ORTLoggingLevel.verbose)
  let ep_options = ORTCoreMLExecutionProviderOptions()
  ep_options.useCPUOnly = true
  try options.appendCoreMLExecutionProvider(with: ep_options)
  session = try ORTSession(env: env, modelPath: modelPath, sessionOptions: options)
```

Did a test with the sample code and ORT 1.9 - verified that some logs do show up after updating the options: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/tree/main/mobile/examples/basic_usage/ios

```diff
diff --git a/mobile/examples/basic_usage/ios/OrtBasicUsage/SwiftOrtBasicUsage.swift b/mobile/examples/basic_usage/ios/OrtBasicUsage/SwiftOrtBasicUsage.swift
index aa4a508..ee10c63 100644
--- a/mobile/examples/basic_usage/ios/OrtBasicUsage/SwiftOrtBasicUsage.swift
+++ b/mobile/examples/basic_usage/ios/OrtBasicUsage/SwiftOrtBasicUsage.swift
@@ -38,7 +38,7 @@ func SwiftOrtAdd(_ a: Float, _ b: Float) throws -> Float {
   // First, we create the ORT environment.
   // The environment is required in order to create an ORT session.
   // ORTLoggingLevel.warning should show us only important messages.
-  let env = try ORTEnv(loggingLevel: ORTLoggingLevel.warning)
+  let env = try ORTEnv(loggingLevel: ORTLoggingLevel.verbose)

   // Next, we will create some ORT values for our input tensors. We have two
   // floats, `a` and `b`.
@@ -62,11 +62,17 @@ func SwiftOrtAdd(_ a: Float, _ b: Float) throws -> Float {
     elementType: valueDataType,
     shape: valueShape)

+  let sessionOptions = try ORTSessionOptions()
+  try sessionOptions.setLogSeverityLevel(ORTLoggingLevel.verbose)
+  let coremlEpOptions = ORTCoreMLExecutionProviderOptions()
+  coremlEpOptions.useCPUOnly = true
+  try sessionOptions.appendCoreMLExecutionProvider(with: coremlEpOptions)
+
   // Now, we will create an ORT session to run our model.
   // One can configure session options with a session options object
   // (ORTSessionOptions).
   // We use the default options with sessionOptions: nil.
-  let session = try ORTSession(env: env, modelPath: modelPath, sessionOptions: nil)
+  let session = try ORTSession(env: env, modelPath: modelPath, sessionOptions: sessionOptions)

   // A session provides methods to get the model input and output names.
   // We will confirm that they are what we expect.
```

When convert onnx to ort, should `python -m onnxruntime.tools.convert_onnx_models_to_ort` also enable `--use_coreml`? I used the stock pip installed 1.9.0 onnx library and if I tried to enable `--use_coreml` when use that tool to convert, it prompts `The CoreML Execution Provider was not included in this build of ONNX Runtime`. If this is needed, do I have to build a python wheel with `--use_coreml` to make the model compatible for coreml ep on device?

I think it depends on the optimization level specified in the conversion (which defaults to "all"). If using "all", you'll want to build the wheel with `--use_coreml`. You can try converting with "basic" optimization with the default onnxruntime package.
More info here: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/performance/mobile-performance-tuning.html
But the docs may not be up to date - I believe the CoreML-aware ORT format model is supported now. @gwang-msft please correct me if I've got any of that wrong.

Yes, the CoreML-aware ORT format is supported. However, please try the conversion with `--optimization_level basic` first, before you build you own ONNX Runtime pypi package.
Even the entire graph has nothing can be supported by CoreML execution provider, the information should be output as logs from CoreML execution provider.
